        <property name="text" class="ptolemy.kernel.util.StringAttribute" value="NOTE: the &quot;img&quot; elements in StringConst actors refer to &#10;files with a path relative to the resourceLocation&#10;parameters of the WebServer.  &#10;&#10;The first resourceLocation is by default&#10;the directory that the current model is in.&#10;&#10;The syntax &lt;img src=&quot;/img/Icon.gif&quot; /&gt; &#10;is a GET request to the web server.  &#10;First the web server determines which handler &#10;is mapped to URLs with the prefix /img.&#10;In this case, there is no such handler, so the server&#10;looks in the directory where the model is stored.&#10;In this case, the model is in&#10;$PTII/org/ptolemy/ptango/demo/WebServerDE&#10;so the file is&#10;$PTII/org/ptolemy/ptango/demo/WebServerDE/img/Icon.gif.&#10;&#10;The syntax &lt;img src=&quot;/files/PtolemySmallIcon.gif&quot;/&gt;,&#10;by contrast, delegates to the handler with prefix &quot;/files&quot;,&#10;which is set to look for files in the directory&#10;&quot;$PTII/org/ptolemy/ptango/demo/files&quot;.&#10;&#10;A ResourceHandler is a Jetty class that knows how &#10;to return files as part of an HttpResponse.&#10;&#10;Note that the resourcePath prefix does NOT have to &#10;be part of the resourceLocation's path anywhere.  &#10;In this example there is no /files in&#10;$PTII/org/ptolemy/ptango/demo/WebServerDE/img/Icon.gif&#10; &#10;You can add as many FileParameters&#10;as you like to the WebServer, and these&#10;directories or URLs will be searched for files.&#10;&#10;For example, StringConst3 specifies a file&#10;&quot;PtolemyIISmall.gif&quot;, which is stored in the&#10;WebServer's resourceLocation2, which has&#10;value &quot;$PTII/doc/img&quot; so &#10;&lt;img src=&quot;/files/PtolemyIISmallIcon.gif&quot; /&gt;&#10;maps to&#10;&quot;$PTII/doc/img/PtolemyIISmall.gif&quot;.&#10;&#10;&#10;">
        </property>
